Trouble, and &s;ave Time and Charges, by pointing out the be&s;t Remedies at fir&s;t, &s;uch as are ea&s;ie&s;t to be got, and &s;uch as make the &s;peedie&s;t Cures; and the Reader may be a&s;&s;ured they have been experimental|ly confirmed by a Practice of thirty Years. The Book is drawn up in a Manner calculated for a Gen|tleman's Pocket, &s;uppo&s;ing him upon a Journey; and no Man, who values his Hor&s;e &s;hould travel without it.</P>
